---
/**
 * Hub: bonus withholding, flat vs aggregate. The worked example is computed here
 * by the same bonusTax() the island uses, so the prose figures cannot drift from
 * the calculator.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import BonusTaxCalculator from '../../components/calculators/BonusTaxCalculator.tsx';
import { bonusTax } from '../../lib/withholding';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

// Ohio, single: a $10,000 bonus on a $50,000 salary. Chosen because the marginal
// bracket sits below 22%, so the two methods visibly disagree.
const ex = bonusTax(10000, 50000, 'OH', 'single');
const flatOver = ex.flat.total - ex.aggregate.total;
---

<Base
  title="Bonus tax calculator 2026 — flat vs aggregate withholding"
  description="See how much of your bonus you actually keep in 2026. Compare the 22% flat method against the aggregate method, with federal, FICA and state withholding."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Bonus tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Your bonus is not taxed at a higher rate — it is <em>withheld</em> differently, and the difference is temporary.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    The single most common belief about bonuses is wrong: a bonus is not taxed
    more than your salary. It is often <em>withheld</em> more, because employers
    can use a flat 22% federal rate on supplemental pay instead of your normal
    marginal rate. At tax time both methods settle to the same bill — the only
    question is whether you lend the IRS money in the meantime.
  </p>

  <BonusTaxCalculator client:load presetState="OH" />

  <h2>Worked example — a {formatMoney(10000)} bonus on a {formatMoney(50000)} salary</h2>
  <p>
    A single filer in Ohio earning {formatMoney(50000)} receives a {formatMoney(10000)}
    bonus. FICA takes {formatMoney(ex.flat.fica)} and Ohio takes {formatMoney(ex.flat.state)}
    either way. The federal piece is where the two methods split:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Method</th><th>Federal withheld</th><th>FICA</th><th>State</th><th>Take-home now</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Flat 22%</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.flat.federal)}</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.flat.fica)}</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.flat.state)}</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.flat.net)}</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Aggregate (marginal)</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.aggregate.federal)}</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.aggregate.fica)}</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.aggregate.state)}</td>
        <td>{formatMoney(ex.aggregate.net)}</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Here the flat method withholds {formatMoney(flatOver)} more than the aggregate
    method, because this filer's marginal bracket is below 22%. That extra
    {formatMoney(flatOver)} is not lost — it comes back as a larger refund. The
    flip happens above roughly {formatMoney(200000)}, where the marginal rate
    passes 22% and the flat method starts withholding too <em>little</em>, leaving
    a bill in April instead.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is my bonus taxed at 22%?</h3>
    <p>
      No. 22% is a federal <em>withholding</em> rate your employer may apply to
      supplemental pay, not a tax rate. Your bonus is ordinary income, taxed in
      your regular brackets when you file. If 22% was withheld and your real rate
      is lower, the difference returns as a refund.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why did my employer take out so much?</h3>
    <p>
      Most likely the flat 22% method on a bonus that, for you, sits in the 10%
      or 12% bracket. That over-withholds now and evens out at filing. Some
      payroll systems also lump the bonus into one paycheck and use the aggregate
      method, which can withhold at a high marginal rate for that one check.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can I have less withheld from a bonus?</h3>
    <p>
      The method is your employer's choice, not yours. What you can do is adjust
      your regular W-4 so the rest of your year withholds less, offsetting a bonus
      that was over-withheld. The <a href="/w4-withholding-calculator/">W-4
      withholding calculator</a> shows whether you are on track for the year.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What about a bonus over $1 million?</h3>
    <p>
      Federal withholding on supplemental pay above $1 million in a year is a flat
      37% on the excess, not 22%. This calculator models the ordinary case below
      that threshold.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does a bonus affect my Social Security tax?</h3>
    <p>
      Only up to the annual wage base. Social Security tax stops once your wages
      for the year pass that base; Medicare has no cap, so its 1.45% applies to
      the whole bonus. The calculator accounts for how much of the wage base your
      salary has already used.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/w4-withholding-calculator/">W-4 withholding calculator</a> — are you on track for the year?</li>
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck calculator</a> — take-home on your regular salary</li>
    <li><a href="/raise-calculator/">Raise calculator</a> — is a raise worth more than a one-off bonus?</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Withholding estimate for the 2026 tax year. Your final tax is settled on your
    return, not by the withholding method. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
